\begin_layout Section
Imperfectly Competitive Markets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A monopoly is different from a competitive firm in the fact that it has
 
\series bold
market power
\series default
, thus it is a price 
\series bold
maker
\series default
 (and not a price 
\series bold
taker
\series default
).
 Once the marginal cost & revenue are equated - the optimal level is found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Deadweight loss 
\series default
- potential efficient transactions are not carried out, because the monopoly
 charges more and sells less.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A monopoly has ability to exploit its market power, by extracting the maxium
 price each customer is willing to pay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Monopolistic Competition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perfect competition and monopoly are two extremes.
 
\series bold
Monopolistic competition
\series default
 is in between: many firms sell similar but not identical products (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substitutes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 
\series bold
Product differentiation
\series default
: by firms, branding (e.g apartments, books, unlike gas).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the one hand, there is market power (monopoly-like), but on the other
 hand - there is competition, because there are (imperfect) substitutes.
 The existence of the market power is derived from the 
\series bold
uniqueness and differentiation
\series default
 of the products.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the short-run, it is quite similar to any other monopoly.
 As opposed to a regular monopoly, which faces 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

market
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 demand, a competitive monopoly faces only the direct exact demand of its
 specific product.
 Everything else is the same: Equating 
\begin_inset Formula $MR$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $MC$
\end_inset

, finding the optimal Q, P and profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The minimum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $AC$
\end_inset

 curve is where it crosses the 
\begin_inset Formula $MC$
\end_inset

 curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimizing output doesn't guarantee a positive profit.
 The rectangle between the price-quantity point and the average cost is
 the total profit.
 If the average cost is above the price, profit will be negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the long-run, a free market entry/exit is assumed, which must 
\series bold
push the profit of each firm to zero
\series default
.
 Equilibrium conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula $P=AC$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $MR=MC$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $AC$
\end_inset

 must be tangent to the demand curve.
 Otherwise, there could have been a (quantity) point where the charged price
 (according to the demand curve) would be higher than the average cost,
 which would imply economic profict, contrary to the above onstraint.
\end_layout

