: 2 playes, 2 possible actions for each one of them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Prisoner's Dilemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2 banks have a dilemma of whether to launch an expensive marketing campaign.
 If both don't advertise, each will have half of the market.
 If both advertise - they get 
\begin_inset Formula $30\%$
\end_inset

 each (20 is the cost of the campaign).
 In case one bank advertise and its rival doesn't - the market is divided
 70%-10%.
 Both banks will advertise.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Domino strategy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - for 
\series bold
each
\series default
 option, each bank is better off if it advertises (one is preferable than
 the other, 
\series bold
no matter
\series default
 what the rival chooses).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Nash equilibrium
\series default
 is a strategies profile which gives best possible response to all others
 (no one has a profitable deviation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Coordination Game (Stag-Hare)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no domino strategy, yet there are two NE: (stag, stag), (hare,
 hare) and mixed one.
 A refinement mechanism - choosing the more plausible outcome.
 
\series bold
Pareto dominance
\series default
 - all players understand that choosing (stag, stag) is better for all.
 
\series bold
Risk dominance
\series default
 - assigning equal probabilities to each rival outcome, thus choosing (stag,
 stag) because of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average outcome
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hawk-Dove
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2 individuals who fight over the ownership on some asset (
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

).
 There are 2 strategies to handle it: aggressively, or deal.
 The fight has a cost (
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

), and assume 
\begin_inset Formula $v/2<c$
\end_inset

.
 There are two asymmetric NE: (dove, hawk), (hawk, dove).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $v/2>c$
\end_inset

, the game become the prisoner's dilemma game.
 There is a third (mixed) strategy.
 Pure strategy means choosing some specific option.
 Mixed strategy means playing each action with some probability,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Mixed Strategy Equilibrium
\series default
: Playing each action with probability, so that the rival is 
\series bold
indifferent
\series default
 between its actions - calculated by equating the expected outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cournot Gane (Duopoly)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume a demand curve defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $P=12-Q$
\end_inset

.
 2 firms, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}+q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $TC_{1}=6+2q_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $TC_{2}=4+4q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Whatever the rival is doing, if my quantity increases, the total quantity
 increases, thus the price decreases, which affects the profits of the rival
 and its decisions.
 First order condition (
\begin_inset Formula $MC-MR=0$
\end_inset

) yields the 
\series bold
best response function
\series default
 for each firm.
 NE is when BRs are to each other (2 equations, 2 variables).
 Actions to crowd out rivals and become a monopoly can be logical in theory,
 but are rare in reality (losses can't be accomodated by shareholders) and
 can't be sustained for the long-term (once a firm becomes a monopoly, past
 players can enter back).
\end_layout

