\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sequential Games
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Play in turns, instead of playing simultaneously.
 The 
\series bold
history
\series default
 is known.
 The game is described using a 
\series bold
decision tree
\series default
.
 For example - persuading small/big hedge funds to invest.
 The big one requires more efforts to persuade.
 The notion of success depends on the collaboration of 2 investors - if
 each one of them approaches a different hedge fund, they will fail.
 Each player's strategy set can include actions dependent on the history
 (e.g do X/Y, and do same/opposite of the previous player).
 There are several equilibriums here, though some of them are 
\series bold
unreliable
\series default
 (why would Megan play 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

always S
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if Harry plays B and she knows it? - It's not a sensible promise, which
 means an unpredictable model, that needs to be refined.
 
\series bold
Subgame Perfect NE
\series default
 - leave only those NE, where the NEs are 
\series bold
reliable
\series default
 (stick only to those strategies which will 
\series bold
always
\series default
 be implemented, by using 
\series bold
backwards induction
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the main idea in sequential game is that 
\series bold
those who act second can make an optimal decision for them, and those who
 play first can foresee it
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stackelberg Game
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamic version of the Cournot game.
 The first firm choses how much to produce, then the second one observes
 that and makes its choice.
 The first firm 
\series bold
can foresee
\series default
 the reaction of the second one.
 Using backward induction, the best response of the second firm is the same
 as in Cournot Game.
 The difference is that now we can 
\series bold
plug in
\series default
 that function in the first firm's first-order condition (because it 
\series bold
foresees
\series default
 the reaction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First-move advantage: the first firm outcrowds the second one.
\end_layout

